        {
          "severity": "P1",
          "line_approx": 22,
          "issue": "WRIGHT'S LAW MISLABELLING: `learningCurve(t, lcoe0, rate) = lcoe0 * Math.pow(1 - rate, t)` implements exponential time-decay, NOT Wright's Law. Wright's Law is LCOE(C) = LCOE_0 * (C/C_0)^(-b) where C is cumulative capacity (experience), not time. The UI label at line 297 says 'Wright's Law: LCOE(t) = LCOE0 * (1-r)^t' — this is an incorrect attribution. The formula is a time-exponential learning approximation, not the classical Wright/experience curve.",
          "fix": "Rename function to `timeDecayCost` and update UI description to: 'Exponential cost reduction (Wright's Law approximation): LCOE(t) = LCOE0 * (1-r)^t, r = annual learning rate'. Or reimplement with cumulative capacity as independent variable."
        },
        {
          "severity": "P1",
          "line_approx": 112,
          "issue": "DEAD CODE — unused variable: `const t = yr - 2020;` at line 112 inside buildTechTrajectory(). This computed value t is never used — the sCurve call on line 113 uses `yr` (absolute year) directly, and learningCurve on line 114 uses `yr - 2024`. The dead `t` variable suggests the author intended relative-year inputs for sCurve but the implementation correctly uses absolute years (both t and t_mid are in absolute year format).",
          "fix": "Remove `const t = yr - 2020;` (line 112) as it is unused and misleading."
        },
